               <p>Q. In August did the prisoner lodge in your house - A. Yes, in the one pair of stairs front room; I slept in the back room on the same floor.</p>
               <p>Q. Had you any salt spoons there - A. Yes, two; they were silver; I missed them out of the trunk in that room: I charged the prisoner with having taken them; she gave me the duplicate; I went to the pawnbrokers; I there found my two silver salt-spoons; I knew them to be mine.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18130915-47-person463">
                  JOHN 
                  MATTHEWS
               <interp inst="t18130915-47-person463" type="surname" value="MATTHEWS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130915-47-person463" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130915-47-person463" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. On the 31st of August, the prisoner pledged these two silver salt-spoons. I lent her three shillings and sixpence upon them.</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. They are my spoons.</p>


               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was in great distress; I had been without victuals three days.</p>
               <p>
